  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Cameroon: upholding human rights in the context of Boko Haram and the Anglophone crisis</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Cameroon is plagued by two violent conflicts:
- After waning briefly in 2018, 2019 was marked by a resurgence of Boko Haram and its offshoot ISWAP, carrying out deadly attacks in the Far North of Cameroon. Even though the government claims to have largely controlled Boko Haram, at least 275 people have been killed and others mutilated or kidnapped during this resurgence. The attacks continued notably in January and February 2020. 
- The conflict between government troops and separatists continues in the Anglophone regions (North-West and South-West); a case in point was a massacre in the village of Ngarbuh on 14 February 2020, uncovered by Human Rights Watch, in which government forces and armed ethnic Fulani killed at least 21 civilians, including 13 children and 1 pregnant woman (national CSOs put the number of casualties at least 35), both in crossfire with separatists, as well as while burning houses in the village. The reaction of the government has as usual been to deny this first, blame it on the separatists, blame the NGOs releasing the information, and after international pressure to admit and launch a flawed investigation. Both HRW and national CSOs mentioned the incident is just an example of a pattern of violations and abuses, indicating that similar massacres have taken place elsewhere, even though less thoroughly researched.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">For several years, Cameroon has been affected by high levels of insecurity and multiple human rights violations/abuses as a result of an Anglophone crisis, frequent Boko Haram attacks (in the north) and a heavy-handed indiscriminate response by Cameroonian forces, with large numbers of people imprisoned and tortured on terrorism charges. 

Since 2016, AINL sought to strengthen the capacity of local civil society organisations in monitoring, documenting and reporting human rights violations by security forces, including supporting victims to access justice and adequate and effective reparation. Staff and volunteers of two organisations were trained in human rights provisions, in techniques of factfinding and documentation with the aim that these organisations will bring corroborated information to Amnesty International and other international actors. Partners were also supported to perform local and national advocacy to change the behaviour of security forces towards more human rights compliance, to liberate suspects arrested on futile grounds, and to improve prison conditions.</narrative>
  </description>
